{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "What kind of information should be provided about algorithms (perhaps specifically AI systems) to the general public?",
    "This is a pressing question now that governments and companies are using algorithms more and more, with potentially massive impacts such as large-scale discrimination in decision making [see Amnesty International (2021) for an example].",
    "As a result, there is a growing demand for transparency about the use of such systems, not least as one of the basic requirements in the EU AI Act, 1 which in the current draft requires forms of transparency for both high-risk and limited risk systems (Varošanec, 2022).",
    "This should help make users aware that they are interacting with AI systems, as well as show (especially for the high-risk systems) that it is responsible to use these systems.",
    "As such, it is a different kind of transparency than the one at stake in discussions of the explainability of AI systems (Das & Rad, 2020) and in the XAI literature."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "This is a pressing question now that governments and companies are using algorithms more and more, with potentially massive impacts such as large-scale discrimination in decision making [see Amnesty International (2021) for an example].",
    "As a result, there is a growing demand for transparency about the use of such systems, not least as one of the basic requirements in the EU AI Act, 1 which in the current draft requires forms of transparency for both high-risk and limited risk systems (Varošanec, 2022).",
    "As such, it is a different kind of transparency than the one at stake in discussions of the explainability of AI systems (Das & Rad, 2020) and in the XAI literature."
  ]
